  "prompt": "My girlfriend for 4years cheated 3 times. I found out 2 month ago. She started talking to a guy as a friend. He called her babe, what should I do?",
  "response": "Dealing with infidelity is incredibly painful and complex, especially when it has happened multiple times. Here are some steps to consider as you navigate this situation:\n\n1. **Acknowledge Your Feelings**: It\u2019s normal to feel hurt, betrayed, angry, or confused. Take time to process your emotions and be honest with yourself about how her actions have impacted you.\n\n2. **Evaluate the Relationship**: Reflect on the relationship as a whole. Has she shown genuine remorse for her past infidelity? Has she made efforts to rebuild trust? Multiple instances of cheating and engaging in questionable behaviors (like allowing someone to call her \u201cbabe\u201d) may indicate a pattern of disrespect or disregard for your feelings.\n\n3. **Communicate Openly**: Have an honest conversation with her about how this new situation makes you feel. Express your concerns and boundaries clearly. Pay attention to her response\u2014is she dismissive, defensive, or willing to take accountability and make changes?\n\n4. **Set Boundaries**: If you decide to stay in the relationship, establish clear boundaries to protect your emotional well-being. For example, you might ask her to cut off contact with this guy or avoid behaviors that blur the lines of friendship.\n\n5. **Assess Trust**: Trust is the foundation of any relationship. If you find it difficult to trust her again, it may be worth considering whether the relationship is healthy for you. Rebuilding trust takes time, effort, and commitment from both partners.\n\n6. **Seek Support**: Talk to trusted friends, family, or a therapist about what you\u2019re going through. An outside perspective can help you gain clarity, and therapy can provide tools to navigate your emotions and decisions.\n\n7. **Consider Your Worth**: You deserve to be in a relationship where you feel valued, respected, and secure. If this relationship consistently undermines your self-worth or happiness, it may be time to walk away.\n\nUltimately, the decision to stay or leave is yours. Take the time you need to make a choice that aligns with your values, needs, and long-term well-being.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
